Title: TAG - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
Light hearted, easy going, enthusiastic, inguenitive and all round fun this is very refreshing comedy.
It works because of the great cast, creative and well though out gags and sketches, good soundtrack, funny screenplay plus really heartfelt message about friendship and putting your differences aside once in awhile. Movie felt like something new and original, although there are familiar tropes but it is all about adventurous spirit and this one has a plenty. It had heart, it had layers, it isn't dumbed down like it would be if it was made by Adam Sandler and his crew and you just leave it with a smile on your face. 3/5.

Comment: I had the pleasure of hanging-out with Jeremy Renner in a casual setting. He's a very warm, very down-to-Earth kind of guy, and a surprisingly talented pianist, singer, and veritable stand-up comedian. We had an amazing discussion about his career, and  about life in general. He said it has been an honor and a privilege having a role‚Äîespecially how relatable‚Äîso many fans adore, and it's not lost on him how important  it is for them. But remember...despite that fact...he's still just an actor. He gets paid for his portrayals. And while he's thankful and respectful of his fans and the source material that inspires them, when it's all said and done, he's a career professional like anyone else trying to earn a decent living. Credit his his talent that brings the fans that pays the bills. So here's a word of advice: If you're ever fortunate in meeting Mr. Renner, think about how many times people don't show enough common decency not to shout at him by the name of a comic book character, particularly while he's being an ordinary citizen in public, and na√Øvely expect he would be as excited as they are when they do. So try not being quite as obnoxious about it, okay? No matter how much you think he should pay his dues as a celebrity. And if you can get over that, you'll find he's a very cool guy who also happens to be super-famous. P.S.: Thankfully, I didn't end-up finding this out the hard way.

‚Äú... A few years later at a class reunion, Schultheis came up with the unique idea to revive the game, using his newly acquired law degree to draw up a contract establishing a new set of rules for him and his friends. The adult version of their tag game only remains active in the month of February, forcing whichever player winds up as "It" on March 1 to carry that shame throughout the entire year. Since the ten friends live across the United States now, there are also no geographic limits ‚Äî players have flown across the country, enlisted the help of spouses and co-workers, and even burst in on funerals and job interviews to tag one another.‚Äù
